The propellant was coming out for a few milliseconds - then it and the clock stopped. SpaceX posted that igniters need to be inspected.

Excess moisture/salt/ice may have short-out a spark gap. I suspect that the igniters need a heat source like a glow-plug, pilot light, or perhaps hot gas to keep those sections dry.

Or perhaps, redesign the power supply electronics (& software) to supply brute force current through the moisture until the voltage drop rises enough to sustain a "norminal" arc across the spark gaps. Then PWM current keeps the spark gaps hot during count-down holds, engine chill down, helium turbine spin-up, etc.

It also occurs to me that a hot steam/solvent flush would remove conductive salts and hydrocarbon goo from the igniters; maybe build that right into the Raptor engine for the sea-level ignition and shut-down sequences.
